Simulating your own sampling distributions

Next, you’ll apply the dplyr tools to simulate your own sampling distribution of the mean. To do that, you’ll need to take many samples, calculate the sample mean \(\bar{Y}\) for each, and plot the distribution.

Randomly sampling rows

You can take a random sample of rows in your data set using the dplyr function slice_sample(). For example, to sample 5 rows at random from the iris data set, you would do the following:

# If you used the same seed as me, you should get the same answer
set.seed(20210203)
slice_sample(iris, n = 5)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width    Species
## 1          5.2         3.5          1.5         0.2     setosa
## 2          5.8         2.7          3.9         1.2 versicolor
## 3          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2     setosa
## 4          7.0         3.2          4.7         1.4 versicolor
## 5          6.0         2.9          4.5         1.5 versicolor

You could get the same result using the pipe operator like this:

# If you used the same seed as me, you should get the same answer
set.seed(20210203)
iris %>%
  slice_sample(n = 5)
##   Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width    Species
## 1          5.2         3.5          1.5         0.2     setosa
## 2          5.8         2.7          3.9         1.2 versicolor
## 3          4.9         3.0          1.4         0.2     setosa
## 4          7.0         3.2          4.7         1.4 versicolor
## 5          6.0         2.9          4.5         1.5 versicolor

Now try on your to increase the sample size 10.

Randomly sampling rows by group

You may have noticed that we sampled rows from multiple species. What if you want to sample 5 rows from each species? We can use the group_by() function to sampling within groups.

# If you used the same seed as me, you should get the same answer
set.seed(20210203)
iris %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  slice_sample(n = 5)
## # A tibble: 15 x 5

##  3          5.7         3.8          1.7         0.3 setosa

##  5          5.8         4            1.2         0.2 setosa

Repeated sampling

To simulate a sampling distribution, we need to repeatedly randomly sample the “population” (in this case, we’re pretending the iris data set is the entire population). The infer package has a convenient function rep_slice_sample() that will repeat slice_sample() many times. It creates a new column called replicate to index each replicate sample. To randomly sample 5 rows 4 times from Iris setosa, we do:

# If you used the same seed as me, you should get the same answer
set.seed(20210203)
iris %>%
  filter(Species == "setosa") %>%
  rep_slice_sample(n = 5, reps = 4)
## # A tibble: 20 x 6
## # Groups:   replicate [4]
##    replicate Sepal.Length Sepal.Width Petal.Length Petal.Width Species
##        <int>        <dbl>       <dbl>        <dbl>       <dbl> <fct>  
##  1         1          5.2         3.5          1.5         0.2 setosa 
##  2         1          4.5         2.3          1.3         0.3 setosa 
##  3         1          5.7         3.8          1.7         0.3 setosa 
##  4         1          4.9         3            1.4         0.2 setosa 
##  5         1          5.8         4            1.2         0.2 setosa 
##  6         2          5           3            1.6         0.2 setosa 
##  7         2          5.1         3.3          1.7         0.5 setosa 
##  8         2          4.4         3.2          1.3         0.2 setosa 
##  9         2          4.6         3.6          1           0.2 setosa 
## 10         2          4.9         3.1          1.5         0.2 setosa 
## 11         3          4.3         3            1.1         0.1 setosa 
## 12         3          5.4         3.9          1.3         0.4 setosa 
## 13         3          4.7         3.2          1.6         0.2 setosa 
## 14         3          4.8         3            1.4         0.1 setosa

Hint: if that didn’t work, remember that you need load the infer package first.

Now, let’s take 1000 samples of 10 from each species. I’ll show you the code for Iris setosa, then fill in the ___ sections below to do it for it the other species. After, you’ll need to combine the results before summarizing and plotting.

# If you used the same seed as me, you should get the same answer
set.seed(20210203)
setosa_sample_dist <- iris %>%
  filter(Species == "setosa") %>%
  rep_slice_sample(n = 10, reps = 1000)

versicolor_sample_dist <- iris %>%
  filter(Species == ___) %>%
  rep_slice_sample(n = 10, reps = 1000)

virginica_sample_dist <- iris %>%
  filter(Species == ___) %>%
  rep_slice_sample(n = 10, reps = 1000)

You can use the bind_rows() function to combine all three sets of sampling distributions into a single tibble.

iris_sample_dists <- bind_rows(
  setosa_sample_dist, 
  versicolor_sample_dist,
  virginica_sample_dist
)

iris_sample_dists

Now we have a very large set of samples to examine.

Sample mean \(\bar{Y}\)

To look at the distribution of the sample mean, we first need to calculate the sample mean for all 1000 replicates per species. Here is where we combine the power of group_by() and summarize(). This huge number of calculations can be done for Sepal.Length with the following code:

sepal_length_sample_dists <- iris_sample_dists %>%
  group_by(Species, replicate) %>%
  summarize(Y_bar = mean(Sepal.Length))

sepal_length_sample_dists
## # A tibble: 3,000 x 3
## # Groups:   Species [3]
##    Species replicate Y_bar
##    <fct>       <int> <dbl>
##  1 setosa          1  5.01
##  2 setosa          2  4.91
##  3 setosa          3  5.14
##  4 setosa          4  5.19
##  5 setosa          5  4.87
##  6 setosa          6  4.87
##  7 setosa          7  5.26
##  8 setosa          8  5.04
##  9 setosa          9  4.89
## 10 setosa         10  4.82
## # … with 2,990 more rows

Modify the code above to calculate sample means for Petal.Length.

Plot the sampling distribution \(\bar{Y}\)

We can apply the ggplot() tools we’ve already learned to plot a multiple histogram to compare the sampling distributions in each species.

ggplot(sepal_length_sample_dists, aes(Y_bar, fill = Species)) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.5, position = "identity", bins = 30) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d()

See if you remember how to use facet_grid() to put each Specie in it’s own panel like this:

Standard error of the mean

The standard error of the mean helps us quantify our uncertainty about our estimate of the population mean. But it’s also a population parameter given by the population standard deviation divided by the square-root of the sample size: \(\sigma / \sqrt{n}\). Let’s again pretend that the iris data set is the “population”, the population standard deviation for Sepal.Length is:

Species \(\sigma\)
setosa 0.35
versicolor 0.51
virginica 0.62

Now calculate the population standard error of the mean for a sample size of 10. You should get:

Species \(\sigma\) \(\sigma/\sqrt{n}\)
setosa 0.35 0.1106797
versicolor 0.51 0.1612762
virginica 0.62 0.1960612

Let’s compare the population standard error of the mean to what we obtain from our simulations. Remember that the standard error of the mean is simply the standard deviation of the sampling distribution. That means we can get the answer by using the sd() function on our simulated sampling distribution.

sepal_length_sample_dists %>%
  group_by(Species) %>%
  summarize(SE_Ybar = sd(Y_bar))
## # A tibble: 3 x 2
##   Species    SE_Ybar
##   <fct>        <dbl>
## 1 setosa       0.101
## 2 versicolor   0.151
## 3 virginica    0.176

Notice that we had to first group by Species, then summarize by taking the standard deviation of all of our sample means.

Are the population standard errors of the mean close to what you calculated from the simulations? Are the standard errors what you expected given the multiple histogram figure above?

Sample standard error of the mean

\(\mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}}\)) quantifies our uncertainty in our estimate of the population mean, \(\bar{Y}\). Specifically, \(\mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}}\) is the standard deviation of sampling distribution for \(\bar{Y}\). The equation for the \(\mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}}\) is the sample standard deviation divided by the square-root of the sample size:

\[ \mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}} = \frac{s}{\sqrt{n}} \]

There’s no function in R to calculate \(\mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}}\), but you know the functions for sample standard deviation and square-root. Use R to calculate the sample standard error of the mean for the following numbers:

2.16 -0.79 -0.18 1.62 -0.98 -1.15 -0.15 1.34 1.96 1.74

You should get \(\mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}}\) = 0.419.

95% confidence intervals

Confidence intervals are a way to show the plausible range of parameter values given the data. 95% confidence intervals will include the true population parameter 95% of the time. We’ll learn ways to calculate confidence intervals for different parameters throughout the class. Today, we’ll use the “2 SE” rule to approximate 95% confidence intervals for the sample mean \(\bar{Y}\). The lower bound and upper bounds of the approximate 95% confidence interval using the 2 SE rule are:

\[ \text{lower CI}: \bar{Y} - 2 \times \mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}} \] \[ \text{upper CI}: \bar{Y} + 2 \times \mathrm{SE}_{\bar{Y}} \] Use the mean() functions and standard error of the mean to calculate the confidence interval for the data you used in the last section. You should get:

\(\bar{Y}\) Lower CI Upper CI
0.557 -0.2813638 1.395364
